messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /posts/{post}/likes

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  false

- HEAD:
  false

- POST:
  true

- OPTIONS:
  false

- TRACE:
  false

- GET:
  false

- PUT:
  false

- DELETE:
  true

- PATCH:
  false

Explanation:
- The web route file routes/auth.php registers two explicit routes for the same URI: Route::post('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'store']) and Route::delete('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'destroy']). Those map to the controller at app/Http/Controllers/PostLikeController.php, so the full path for this controller's destroy implementation is /posts/{post}/likes.
- Because the code explicitly registers POST and DELETE for that path, POST and DELETE are marked acceptable. The destroy method itself is invoked for DELETE requests.
- No other HTTP methods (HEAD, GET, PUT, PATCH, OPTIONS, TRACE, or a wildcard that would allow all methods) are registered in the code for this path, so they are marked unacceptable. (Note: there are similar API routes under routes/api.php but those are under the prefix v1 and reference a different controller class App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostLikeController â€” the path for those would be /v1/posts/{post}/likes.)
